From Figure 5, the trend that should be most apparent is the proportion of beef and buffalo being consumed compared to the proportion of poultry. Not only has the consumption of beef and buffalo reduced in the past years, but it is expected to decrease even more by 2050! On the other hand, the proportion of poultry has been increasing and is predicted to continue rising as well. One of the reasons for this is because of the concerns about the consumption of too much â€œred meatâ€ which includes beef, goat and pork. These types of meat have greater amounts of saturated fats and bad cholesterol, which if consumed regularly can increase the risks of type 2 diabetes, stroke and colorectal cancer. Additionally, when compared to the price of poultry options such as chicken, these options become less desirable for many families around the world. We can recall from Figure 4 that cattle was one of the largest polluters of methane whereas poultry was amongst the least. So, this trend that we are seeing is a positive sign for our future because by decreasing demand for animals such as cattle and increasing demand for poultry, we will be able to decrease greenhouse gas emissions globally. Our suggested alternative to agricultural meat is to begin consuming plant-based meat! Figure 6 shows us what would happen when switching over to plant-based meat. Plant-based meat is considered to be a substitute for traditional meat because of how similar it tastes to its meat counterpart. This visualization further shows us the percentage of greenhouse gasses that are emitted by the plant-based versions of some of your favorite burgers. The most significant reduction of greenhouse gasses comes from consuming a plant-based beef burger as opposed to a regular beef burger. The percentages are not as high when considering other meats such as chicken and pork but we have to remember, these animals released very little greenhouse gasses into our atmosphere in the first place! Save the world by switching to these great tasting alternatives.
